social_posts.post_text:
I’m really happy to share this new series of paintings that I’ve been working for the last couple of months. Some of these ones started as an iPad sketch or a digital illustration and found their way into a canvas. I find it interesting to try different brushstrokes, sizes, colors, shapes and just ideas about painting in general. Visitors are welcome at the studio for viewing.

All paintings are now available on my shop.

To be honest the third edition of “In the Heat of the Night” took forever. We had delays with paper, with printers, with shipping and we had to throw a whole batch of prints 😭😭😭 and finally @tomkracauer came saving the day and we are releasing the edition this weekend 💙 thanks to everyone that pre ordered and waited patiently. To put things on the world cost time and effort. It is what it is and we try out best. Always. The new prints look awesome ✨👌✨

We printed this one in Riso and it looks great 🧡🧡🧡

💥 OPEN STUDIO THIS SUNDAY 💥

We’ll be opening the studio this weekend to show new paintings, sell prints with discounts, put drawings on the tables, rugs, donuts and coffee and just hanging there to chat and having a nice time.

I’m going to put one of the big hands prints at 50% discount to close the year. This has been an amazing year for me and Macarena and we just want to thank you all. Hope you can make it 🙂🙂🐶

Sunday December 11
11am - 4pm . 977 N Hill St. 
Chinatown, Los Angeles
It’s finally Friday!
I don’t drink but I imagine all this with a soda 🤣

Today at 11am we’ll be doing an open studio to close the year and celebrate the work, the studio and everything in between.

WORLD CHAMPIONS 🙌✨🇦🇷✨🏆⚽️✨ 

Today is all futbol here. 
What an incredible ride! I’m still up on the air. I had to draw something just to come back to reality. I can’t believe how amazing this team is!!!! 🇦🇷🇦🇷🇦🇷VAMOS ARGENTINA!!!

In 2022 I did a global clothing collection with my name on it and suddenly my drawings became garments for people to wear, I started selling paintings and the paintings became bigger and stronger, I printed more silkscreen than ever in all the past years combined all together. We moved to a studio in Chinatown that I had the luck to share with my talented wife @macarenaluzi and just being there feels great. My hands traveled to newspapers covers, apps and websites and I was invited places to talk, draw and create more art than ever in my life. 2022 has been the year that I exercise the more and finally I have a nice work life balance where most of the time. I can’t be thankful enough for all of this and wait! We got a sausage dog this year that is the joy of our studio !!! 2022 is going to be hard to beat but I’m going to give it evrything. Thanks for sharing all these with me. Hope you have a wonderful year 💛

With sprinkles of holidays, fun and playfulness we designed more than 50 pieces and even some animations. I’ll be sharing more over the next couple of weeks but if you are curious the whole project is online on my @behance

They have this nice project going where, every now and then, they publish a music playlist with a cover done by the person holding the album. Usually friends and people that visit their studio in Manhattan. Hope I’m explaining it well :p Anyways, music is coming and these are the two covers I did for the project ✨✨✨✏️ For more studio visits and great music 👌

I’m doing a new series of paintings on paper with this thick line. The idea on these ones is to focus on the structure of the drawings, the character of the lines and use my whole arm and body to paint them. Acrylic painting on these sheets of paper gets really thick and you can see how one line goes on top of another forming almost a weaving.

I painted this drawing in blue and yellow on canvases that are 50 inches tall. With painting I feel you have to explore sizes and colors as you go. Every shape and color reacts different in relation to scale and vibration is not the same when I design colors on a screen so we paint several versions of every drawing at the studio until we feel happy enough with the exploration.

A mural the size of a building and sixty thousand posters are just a portion of the scale of this project with @elrecoleta in Buenos Aires.

Every summer the facade of the building is painted with a new mural and a new cycle of events is organized for everyone that want to join. All free and open with an agenda to educate and provide free entertainment for the public. I’m a big fan of El Recoleta work and is my pleasure to be part of this year  campaign. 

For this year of “Amor de Verano” I painted two kids that are about to kiss and in that anticipation and excitement we can see a world of surrounding explosions and fireworks going wild around them.  There is a bowl full of pins with hearts and hands of every color in all combinations. And there is a series of 4 posters that are given for free every afternoon that show the moment two kids are about to have their first kiss.

I love everything about this project and if you happen to be in Buenos Aires this summer I would recommend a visit.

Advice of the day: Do more things that make you forget to check your phone ✨✨✨✏️
The daily effort from no deliberate program but straight from the heart.

The biggest smile ever, someone ready to go, a bird on the sky, fingers crossed, a supportive gesture, a handfull of pencils and break an egg. And applause. And squeeze the lemon. And more. Because is all about making. All about the process. Not how you do it or how it looks. Not what tool or how much. Just how it feels and how you sustain that feeling. Good morning 💛

A collection of romantic moments 😘

I’m reading Keith Haring’s journal and it’s pretty awesome. I don’t know how I didn’t get to it before. Here is something that stuck with me “Risks are what make the difference between new ideas and re-worked old ideas. If there is an idea that I feel is worthy of my undivided efforts, I will use whatever I have access to. Nothing is sacred to the point of being unchangeable. “

What’s nice about a painting this big is that it changes a room. Light gets tainted with color. It fills the room and becomes part of you right away. If you get close flowers cover you and you can see every brushstroke. This one was a experiment so it has spills, dots, rough lines and a ton of corrections of the composition and I loved it for that. Is all process right there.

I’ll be showing this painting on April 22th at @thejaunt A DECADE OF THE JAUNT at @hashimotocontemporary .
It is up to you to see the beauty of everyday things 👀

I’ll be showing OUT OF THE BLUE at A Decade of @thejaunt opening Saturday, April 22nd at @hashimotocontemporary Los Angeles.

It feels great to start the week with the photos of my first time showing work in China 🤯 hosted by the marvelous team at Brand Magazine. 

The show was part of the  Art Book Exhibition in Guangzhou City and it presented a series of posters that I’ve been doing over the years, both in silkscreen and riso print. It’s a pleasure to see my work in places this far to me. Absolute increible 🤯🤯🤯

This week we sold the last copy of Dare Mighty things and Out of the Blue ( jumbo size )  and I’m really really surprised and just happy on how these prints have become such a big part of my work. In a time where craft and quality is seen sometimes as secondary I believe we should persist into creating with attention to detail, and love for the work we put into the world.

I was invited by the team at @starbucksartprogram to create a piece that fills the room and celebrates the kindness and connection we see every day in the Los Angeles community. Here below you can read something I wrote for this piece:

Title – Home is not a place 
Medium – Acrylic paint on canvas 
Year – 2023

I’m a fan of taking a break and going for a walk around the block, getting a coffee or walking the dog. Just going outside the studio and walk around. I love how these small breaks make me disconnect from the thing I was doing before and gets me talking with someone on the line while getting coffee, listen someone laughing about how my sausage dog wobbles while walking or just the simple fact of crossing eyes with someone and smiling to acknowledge that we are sharing the same moment. 
Public spaces are the extension of our homes. We build a sense of community with these very small and subtle gestures. They are almost unnoticeable but you can tell when someone is being nice to you and it makes you feel comfortable. It is an invitation to belong. A coffee shop puts all of us together and just by existing in the same place at the same time I feel we make the whole experience better.

I’m really happy this piece is going to stay in the Los Angeles Community. Go check it out if you are in the neighborhood.

This workshop given by me and is designed to give ideas on Visual Language & Style in the span of an afternoon. It is for illustrators, art students, graphic designers, animators, painters, film directors, ceramicists, textile artists, architects, desginers of all kinds, curious people or just any person interested in creating images or thinking in visual terms. I’ve learn through the years that editing and publishing work is a task that requires a lot from me. It is easier to create and let go. A painting or a drawing once is done, there is not much to do there. But I’ve also learned that I love to see my work in different mediums, to explore materials and techniques. To share my work with people. To see it travel the world and end on a wall so far from me. 

It is an absolute pleasure to present to you these limited edition silkscreen print in 40x55 inches. Size is so hard to accomplish in silkscreen with flat colors! And I’m really happy to be able to see these two beautiful prints come true after so many years of wanting.

If you are in LA and want to come visit the studio to check them up in person send me an email and we can schedule a visit for you.

Today I am incredibly happy to share this series of sketchbooks done in collaboration with @monoblock that is out and available now!✏️✨✨✨📚 

I like objects that are simple and clean. Gathering ideas and building meaning takes time and effort and I’ve learn the best way is to be alert, always! and take notes of any thoughts. That’s why I love this project so much. Because a small, inexpensive sketchbook is all promise. Some paper and a pencil and you have everything you need.

Each sketchbook has a drawing on  the cover. I treated them as a canvas and I tried to think about how we work, in my case, I draw, take a break, grab a coffee, back to draw until I’m happy and start again trusting the process and wishing a bit of good luck. That’s why you’ll find here a pencil, a smile, a coffee  and the fingers crossed, symbol of hoping something good is going to happen.

Check @monoblock website to get a sketchbook 👍
